Key Findings
Kebumen Regency recorded the highest poverty rate in Central Java at 17.59%.
Wonosobo and Brebes also showed relatively high poverty levels, exceeding 17%.
Semarang City had the lowest poverty rate at 4.34%.
Salatiga City and Pekalongan City were among the regions with the lowest poverty levels.
The average poverty rate in Central Java was 11.01%.
Significant disparities exist between regions with high and low poverty rates.

Discussion:
The analysis indicates that poverty levels vary considerably across regions in Central Java. These differences may be influenced by several factors, including economic structure, urbanization, employment opportunities, educational access, and regional development.
Urban areas generally tend to have lower poverty rates due to greater access to economic activities, infrastructure, and public services. In contrast, several rural regions continue to face challenges related to income generation and economic diversification.
Understanding these regional disparities is important for designing more targeted poverty alleviation and socioeconomic development policies.

Conclusion:
This analysis highlights significant differences in poverty levels among regencies and cities in Central Java in 2020. Kebumen, Wonosobo, and Brebes were identified as the regions with the highest poverty rates, while Semarang City and Salatiga City recorded the lowest rates.
The findings emphasize the importance of equitable development strategies and targeted social programs to reduce poverty and improve welfare across all regions of Central Java.

